{{Infobox NRHP | name = Cadron Settlement | nrhp_type = | image = Cadron_Settlement,_2_of_2.jpg | caption = | nearest_city= [[Conway, Arkansas]] | lat_degrees = 35 | lat_minutes = 6 | lat_seconds = 26 | lat_direction = N | long_degrees = 92 | long_minutes = 32 | long_seconds = 44 | long_direction = W | coord_display = inline,title | locmapin = Arkansas#USA | architect OR builder = | architecture = | added = May 17, 1974 | area = {{convert|150|acre}} | governing_body = Federal | refnum = 74000475<ref name="nris">{{NRISref|version=2010a}}</ref> }} The '''Cadron Settlement''' was the first permanent settlement by white men in what is now central [[Arkansas]]. Archaeological investigation of the area, located on the banks of the [[Arkansas River]], has revealed evidence of prehistoric occupation by Native Americans, and the area is known to have been visited by French explorers in the 18th century. It was settled about 1810 by John McElmurry, and was on the main mail route between the [[Arkansas Post]] and [[Hot Springs, Arkansas|Hot Springs]]. From 1825 to 1828 it was the county seat of [[Conway County, Arkansas|Conway County]]. By 1834 the community had declined in importance, when it was described as virtually abandoned in by an Army soldier leading a band of migrating Cherokees on the [[Trail of Tears]]. The camp they established nearby was the site of a [[cholera]] outbreak.<ref name=NRHP>{{cite web|url=http://www.arkansaspreservation.com/national-register-listings/cadron-settlement|title=Summary description of Cadron Settlement|publisher=Arkansas Preservation|accessdate=2016-02-06}}</ref>
The archaeologically important settlement site was listed on the [[National Register of Historic Places]] in 1974.<ref name="nris"/>
==Cadron Settlement Park== The site is located in the public Cadron Settlement Park, operated by the city of [[Conway, Arkansas|Conway]] under a lease from the [[U.S. Army Corps of Engineers]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Cadron Settlement Park|url=http://www.arkansas.com/attractions/detail/cadron-settlement-park/23961|publisher=Arkansas Department of Parks & Tourism|accessdate=15 August 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Cadron Settlement|url=http://www.encyclopediaofarkansas.net/encyclopedia/entry-detail.aspx?entryID=1107|publisher=Encyclopedia of Arkansas|accessdate=15 August 2016}}</ref>
Cadron Settlement Park features a reconstructed two-story wooden blockhouse, the Cherokee Trail of Tears, a boat launching ramp, hiking trails, restrooms, picnic areas, pavilion, handicapped trails and parking areas, and interpretive signs. The Faulkner Historical Society hosts historic events in the blockhouse.<ref>{{cite web|title=Cadron Blockhouse|url=http://faulknerhistory.org/cadron-block-house/|publisher=Faulkner Historical Society|accessdate=15 August 2016}}</ref>
